I absolutely agree this makes sense.  However I'm primarily concerned about the number of jobs and minutes used. We are [limited](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/learn-github-actions/usage-limits-billing-and-administration#usage-limits) by the total number of concurrent jobs running. 

Current number of jobs and time per event listed below:
| Event             | Jobs | Total time  |
|-------------------|--------|-----------------|
|Push               | ~12  |~120mins   |
| Pull_request | ~15  | ~120 mins |

We do have concurrency groups set on our workflows that help with this, but I'm not sure if our CI can handle it. We can try this, maybe extend the time in between cherry picks?  Also we need to be mindful that the total of allowed concurrent jobs is shared across the argoproj organization.

```
notBefore=Mar  2 10:16:12 2023 GMT
notAfter=Mar 12 10:16:12 2023 GMT
serial=ECD5483932CD2E8C <--- old
```

Step 2: Update the certificate `secret/argocd-server-tls`

```
2023-03-02 11:17:14
subject= /C=NL/O=Argo CD Cert Test number 2/CN=localhost
notBefore=Mar  2 10:17:14 2023 GMT
notAfter=Mar 12 10:17:14 2023 GMT
serial=B850266BA30BFB68

````

Check if the certificate has indeed changed

```
2023-03-02 11:17:14
subject= /C=NL/O=Argo CD Cert Test number 2/CN=localhost
notBefore=Mar  2 10:17:14 2023 GMT
notAfter=Mar 12 10:17:14 2023 GMT
serial=B850266BA30BFB68 <--- new
```

Notice the change now it so fast it happens even within the same second.

This is also visible from the logs:

```
[argocd-server] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="Loading TLS configuration from secret argocd/argocd-server-tls"
[argocd-server] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="Notifying 1 settings subscribers: [0xc00135a960]"
[argocd-server] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="tls certificate modified. reloading certificate"
[dex] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="Loading TLS configuration from secret argocd/argocd-server-tls"
[dex] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="Notifying 1 settings subscribers: [0xc0001866c0]"
[dex] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="dex config unmodified"
[argocd-applicationset-controller] time="2023-03-02T10:17:14Z" level=info msg="Loading TLS configuration from secret argocd/argocd-server-tls"
[argocd-application-controller] time="2023-03-02T10:17:19Z" level=info msg="Loading TLS configuration from secret argocd/argocd-server-tls
```

In the previous version, the `tlsConfig` variable was set with a single certificate using Certificates field.

However, in this PR's updated version, the `TlsConfig.GetCertificate` method is set instead, which returns the certificate from the `a.settings.Certificate` variable that contains the latest version of certificates. This hook dynamically reloads the certificate as needed, without restarting the server, which could be more efficient and less disruptive to ongoing operations.

This is very much in line with something I've been thinking about for a while too - especially for configuration of cluster add-ons that often require some level of "per cluster" customization.

I found that this is actually already doable today. Instead of storing our `cluster-info` ConfigMap on each target cluster, it would be stored in some central "cluster registry".

In its most simplest case, this cluster registry could be a simple collection of YAML files holding cluster metadata in git.  And then a `merge` combination of the `clusters` and `git-files` generators allow you to template your values overrides. An added benefit of that is that it allows you to construct helm values from only partial variables. Consider this example from a partial `ApplicationSet` template spec:

```yaml
          values: |-
              rbac:
                serviceAccount:
                  annotations:
                    eks.amazonaws.com/role-arn: 'arn:aws:iam::{{awsAccount}}:role/{{name}}-external-dns'
```

Using this proposal, I still couldn't construct such dynamic values.

Using the plugin generator (https://github.com/argoproj/argo-cd/pull/13017) I could also use a simple http api to retrieve the cluster metadata instead of only a git repo.

Example generators config:
```yaml
  - merge:
      mergeKeys:
      - name
      generators:
      - clusters:
          selector:
            matchLabels:
              argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type: cluster
      - git:
          repoURL: https://github.com/myorg/cluster-registry.git
          revision: HEAD
          files:
          - path: cluster-info/*
```

Example cluster-info file:
```yaml
name: "mycluster-prod-us-east-1"
region: "us-east-1"
awsAccount: "123456789012"
clusterFqdn: "mycluster-prod-us-east-1.clusters.mycompany.com"
publicSubnetID: subnet-123456
privateSubnetID: subnet-987654
```

I think instead of disabling all edits in the App Summary page, we should only disable the fields which are related to the `sources` block. For example, editing the app's labels shouldn't be disabled.
